ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we successfully synthesized bimetallic CEW@CuAg NCs based on CEW as the template and the negatively charged SF-CQDs by a one-step hydrothermal carbonization method using silk fibroin (SF) as the carbon source [32]. Then, a novel dual-emission SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs nanocomposite was constituted by electrostatic assembly of SF-CQDs and CEW@CuAg NCs. This synthesis route is simple, mild and cost-effective and provides an ideal green synthesis strategy. In addition, Ag and Cu is cheaper than Au. The dual-emission SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs nanocomposites show ultra-sensitivity and selectivity for CIP detection. The obtained SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs nanocomposites exhibit two emission wavelengths at the same excitation wavelength.The emission intensity of CuAg NCs at 600 nm (F600
                     ) is quenched whereas the emission of SF-CQDS at 440 nm (F440
                     ) is enhanced in the presence of CIP. As such, ratiometric fluorescence analysis (F600
                     /F440
                     ) of CIP can be realized. The synthesis of SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs and detection of CIP is summarized in Scheme 1
                     . Our proposed ratiometric fluorescence method has been applied to determine CIP in honey with good sensitivity and selectivity.

To explore the conditions for the synthesis of CEW@CuAg NCs, various concentrations of NaBH4 and pH were investigated. Fig. S2a and b displays the fluorescence intensity at excitation (Ex) 330 nm/emission (Em) 600 nm of CEW@CuAg NCs synthesized at various pH and different concentrations of NaBH4, respectively. The as-synthesized CEW@CuAg NCs shows the highest emission intensity at 1.5 M NaBH4 and pH 11 as shown in Fig. S2. Fig. S3a and b displays the fluorescence emission spectra of SF-CQDs under different excitations (300–400 nm). The emission peak is red-shifted and the intensity decreases with the increase in the excitation wavelength, indicating that the emission of the as-synthesized SF-CQDs is excitation-dependent. Strongest intensity is obtained at Ex 310 nm/Em 440 nm. Fig. S3b shows the emission spectra of CEW@CuAg NCs under different excitations (300–400 nm). The emission peak is at 600 nm which is not excitation-dependent. Highest intensity is obtained at Ex 330 nm/Em 600 nm. The optical properties of SF-CQDs, CEW@CuAg NCs were investigated and shown in Fig. S3c and d. SF-CQDs has a strong absorption peak at 285 nm which probably arises from electronic transition of n to π* orbital of the surface oxygen group. CEW@CuAg NCs shows an absorption peak at 263 nm which can be attributed to the K-band absorption of the π-system ligands. The absorption spectrum of SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs in Fig. 2e shows the distinct peaks 263 and 285 nm of the SF-CQDs and CEW@CuAg NCs nanoparticles, respectively, confirming that SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs comprises SF-CQDs and CEW@CuAg NCs. The Ex/Em maxima of SF-CQDs and CEW@CuAg NCs are 310/440 and 330/600 nm, respectively. The inset of Fig. S3c shows the pictures of SF-CQDs under sunlight and UV lamp. SF-CQD has light brown color under sunlight but it shows strong blue Em under UV light. CEW@CuAg NCs in the inset of Fig. S3d also shows light brown color under sunlight but it has strong orange-red Em under UV light. SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs in the inset of Fig. 2e displays light brown color under daylight and orange emission under UV light. It is interesting to note that SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs possesses dual Em peaks at 440 and 600 nm when Ex 330 nm, attributing to the Em of SF-CQDs and CEW@CuAg NCs nanoparticles, respectively. As such, it is possible to employ SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs for ratiometric fluorescence analysis. The stability of SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs was investigated and shown in Fig. S4. The fluorescence ratio (F600
                        /F440
                        ) of SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs remains within 60 days, inferring that SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs has good storage stability.

Fig. 3e shows the fluorescence enhancement at 440 nm (F440
) and quenching at 600 nm (F600
) of CQDs/CuAg NCs by CIP. Thus, it is possible to determine CIP by fluorescence ratiometric measurement (F600
/F440
) of CIP. Fig. 3e shows the plot of F440
/F600
 against concentration of CIP (5.0–200.0 μM). F600
/F440
 shows a good linear relationship with CIP concentration and r is 0.9940. The limit of detection (LOD) is determined to be 3.3 μM, indicating that the proposed SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs ratiometric fluorescent probe has potential for CIP analysis. Table 1
 summarizes several other analytical methods for the detection of CIP. Our proposed work is comparable to other methods in terms of linear response range and LOD.

Selectivity is one of the very important analytical evaluation metrics for the developed fluorescent probe S-CQDs/CuAg NCs. Fig. 3f displays the fluorescence spectra ratio (F600
                        /F4400
                        ) of S-CQDs/CuAg NCs in the presence of potential interferents (BSA, D,L-PHE, MET, ALA, DPA, VH, CYS, AA, BEN, SD, BCD, GM, LYS, CFM, DA, and EM) and CIP. The results showed that SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs only responds to CIP, demonstrating that SF-CQDs/CuAg NCs have good selectivity to CIP.
